{
  "slug": "lilo-amp-stitch-friendship-and-the-top-five-movie-friends",
  "title": "‘Lilo & Stitch,’ ‘Friendship,’ and the Top Five Movie Friends",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2025-05-28",
  "runtimeMin": 85,
  "format": "Sean Fennessey and Amanda Dobbins run down the Cannes prizes and a record Memorial Day box office, review the live-action 'Lilo & Stitch' and Tim Robinson's 'Friendship,' then each rank five favorite movie friendships.",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "The Cannes prizes",
      "note": "read from afar; they saw none of the films",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "It Was Just an Accident",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Jafar Panahi's Palme d'Or winner, Neon's sixth straight. Sean notes Neon bought it rather than funding Panahi, and reads jury president Juliette Binoche as a longtime Panahi backer. He was welcomed back to Iran as a hero after years of house arrest, which makes any Oscar campaign geopolitically loaded."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sentimental Value",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Joachim Trier's Grand Prix winner. Renate Reinsve plus Stellan Skarsgard and Dakota Fanning; Sean floats a career-recognition Skarsgard supporting campaign."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sirât",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Oliver Laxe's jury-prize winner. Sean saw only the trailer: a father searching for his daughter amid an EDM festival in the desert."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sound of Falling",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Shared the jury prize."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Secret Agent",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Kleber Mendonca Filho's film took Best Director and Best Actor (Wagner Moura), an unusual double at Cannes. Neon again; Sean expects a long Oscar conversation and a moment for Brazil."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Little Sister",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Nadia Melliti won Best Actress."
        },
        {
          "title": "Young Mothers",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "The Dardenne brothers won Best Screenplay."
        },
        {
          "title": "Resurrection",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Bi Gan's special-award winner, picked up by Janus; likely a New York Film Festival play late in the year."
        },
        {
          "title": "Nouvelle Vague",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Richard Linklater's film about the making of Godard's 'Breathless,' bought by Netflix. Their third straight Linklater acquisition after 'Hit Man' and 'Apollo 10 1/2.' Netflix and Janus were the only non-Neon, non-Mubi buyers at the festival."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "discussion",
      "heading": "A record Memorial Day box office",
      "note": "people went to the movies again",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Mission: Impossible - The Final Reckoning",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "$77 million, roughly the franchise average and technically its biggest three-day opening (IMAX, an unusual Memorial Day slot). Sean thinks the merely-fine result settles nothing about whether it's the last one."
        },
        {
          "title": "Final Destination Bloodlines",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "$95 million in 11 days, off a modest guess. Originally slated as an HBO Max title; the lesson, again, is to put horror in theaters."
        },
        {
          "title": "Sinners",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Still running at over $260 million domestic, $300 million-plus internationally, pre-PVOD."
        },
        {
          "title": "Thunderbolts",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Headed toward roughly $190 million; a report pegged a possible $100 million loss. Sean ties its fate, and Marvel's centrality, to 'The Fantastic Four.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "The Last Rodeo",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Angel Studios release starring, and co-written by, Neal McDonough; about $7.5 million."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Lilo & Stitch’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Lilo & Stitch",
          "year": 2025,
          "note": "Dean Fleischer Camp's live-action remake of the 2002 film, with Maia Kealoha and a returning Tia Carrere, Amy Hill, and Jason Scott Lee. It opened to $183 million, a record Memorial Day weekend, powered by young-millennial nostalgia. Amanda was offended by plot changes that make the adults crueler; both were mixed while noting it's clearly landing hardest with 9- and 10-year-olds. Sean's daughter was engaged in the theater but said nothing about it afterward. The new ending, sending Nani off to college rather than keeping the family together, has upset original fans; Amanda's fine with it. Billy Magnussen's Pleakley drew the most praise."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "‘Friendship’",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Friendship",
          "year": 2024,
          "note": "Andrew DeYoung's A24 comedy, picked up out of TIFF, starring Tim Robinson as a marketing guy whose bond with a charismatic weatherman neighbor (Paul Rudd) curdles into obsession. Both found it a durational but very good stretch of a sketch premise, closer to Robinson's discomfiting 'I Think You Should Leave' register than to a broad buddy comedy; Sean invokes 'Taxi Driver.' Highlights: the a cappella hip-hop scene, Connor O'Malley in the garage, and Kate Mara playing it dead straight. Sean expects instant cult status once it hits Max."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "list",
      "heading": "The Top Five Movie Friends",
      "note": "two lists, five apiece; counted down 5 to 1",
      "picks": [
        {
          "title": "E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial",
          "year": 1982,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 1. Elliott and E.T.: a lonely boy who builds his whole emotional life around the friend who shows up. Sean's pick as the template these creature-friend movies, 'Lilo & Stitch' included, are chasing."
        },
        {
          "title": "Y Tu Mamá También",
          "year": 2001,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 2. Julio and Tenoch, Cuaron's road movie: two homies who think they've said everything to each other, then find out otherwise across the trip."
        },
        {
          "title": "Husbands",
          "year": 1970,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 3. Cassavetes with Ben Gazzara and Peter Falk as old friends crashing out after a fourth friend dies. Sean calls it a kind of prequel to 'Friendship.'"
        },
        {
          "title": "Ghost World",
          "year": 2001,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 4. Enid and Rebecca (Thora Birch, Scarlett Johansson) drifting apart as they age; a sophisticated portrait of a friendship that gently loosens without a blowup."
        },
        {
          "title": "Superbad",
          "year": 2007,
          "by": "Sean Fennessey",
          "note": "No. 5, and a semi-joke: McLovin and the cops (Bill Hader, Seth Rogen), who bond for real and are genuinely hurt when the lie comes out."
        },
        {
          "title": "Good Will Hunting",
          "year": 1997,
          "by": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "note": "No. 1. Will and Chuckie; Affleck's 'best part of my day' speech as the clearest statement of wanting the best for a friend, even if it means losing him."
        },
        {
          "title": "My Girl",
          "year": 1991,
          "by": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "note": "No. 2. Vada and Thomas (Anna Chlumsky, Macaulay Culkin), a friendship at that tricky age; the ending gutted both hosts as kids. Amanda's mainstream counterweight to Sean's art picks."
        },
        {
          "title": "Frances Ha",
          "year": 2012,
          "by": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "note": "No. 3. Frances and Sophie, close friends and roommates growing apart in their late 20s; the hurt and love portrayed without melodrama. Amanda loves Mickey Sumner's performance."
        },
        {
          "title": "Ocean's Eleven",
          "year": 2001,
          "by": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "note": "No. 4. Danny and Rusty, the wordless-shorthand ideal; Amanda likens it to Sean and Chris Ryan. Thirty years of trust, and they do crimes."
        },
        {
          "title": "Girls Trip",
          "year": 2017,
          "by": "Amanda Dobbins",
          "note": "No. 5. The Flossy Posse; Amanda's group-of-women pick, both funnier than expected and moving (Regina Hall's closing speech). 'Sex and the City' ruled out as TV-first."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
